From: tawc
Origin: own

Android's seccomp filter for app processes terminates the process with
SIGSYS on `setgid()` / `setuid()` calls. xorg-server's `Popen()` does
`setgid(getgid())` / `setuid(getuid())` in the child to drop saved-uid
privileges before exec'ing — but on Android there are no privileges to
drop (the compositor process is the app uid, full stop), so the calls
are a no-op semantically and a hard kill in practice. Skip them on
Android.
--- a/os/utils.c
+++ b/os/utils.c
@@ -1343,10 +1343,12 @@ Popen(const char *command, const char *type)
 #endif
         return NULL;
     case 0:                    /* child */
+#ifndef __ANDROID__
         if (setgid(getgid()) == -1)
             _exit(127);
         if (setuid(getuid()) == -1)
             _exit(127);
+#endif
         if (*type == 'r') {
             if (pdes[1] != 1) {
                 /* stdout */
